<WRITING SEX="FEMALE" PERSON="BRWWRITER"><ORLANDOHEADER TYPE="text"><FILEDESC><TITLESTMT><DOCTITLE>Jane Johnson: writing</DOCTITLE></TITLESTMT><PUBLICATIONSTMT><AUTHORITY>Orlando Project</AUTHORITY></PUBLICATIONSTMT><SOURCEDESC>Based on original research by members of the Orlando Project.</SOURCEDESC></FILEDESC><REVISIONDESC><RESPONSIBILITY RESP="MPO" WORKSTATUS="SUB" WORKVALUE="I"><DATE>1 December 2010</DATE><ITEM>Initial document given to tagger.</ITEM></RESPONSIBILITY><RESPONSIBILITY RESP="IMG" WORKSTATUS="RWT" WORKVALUE="I"><DATE>4 March 2011</DATE><ITEM></ITEM></RESPONSIBILITY><RESPONSIBILITY RESP="IMG" WORKSTATUS="RWT" WORKVALUE="P"><DATE>9 March 2011</DATE><ITEM></ITEM></RESPONSIBILITY><RESPONSIBILITY RESP="IMG" WORKSTATUS="RWT" WORKVALUE="C"><DATE>13 March 2011</DATE><ITEM>rbv c, ready for cas</ITEM></RESPONSIBILITY><RESPONSIBILITY RESP="KGL" WORKSTATUS="CAS" WORKVALUE="I"><DATE>5 April 2011</DATE><ITEM></ITEM></RESPONSIBILITY><RESPONSIBILITY RESP="KGL" WORKSTATUS="CAS" WORKVALUE="I"><DATE>8 April 2011</DATE><ITEM></ITEM></RESPONSIBILITY><RESPONSIBILITY RESP="IMG" WORKSTATUS="RWT" WORKVALUE="C"><DATE>4 May 2011</DATE><ITEM></ITEM></RESPONSIBILITY><RESPONSIBILITY RESP="KGL" WORKSTATUS="CAS" WORKVALUE="P"><DATE>7 May 2011</DATE><ITEM>Cas-ing and tag reports are done but there are a few researchnotes that need answering. </ITEM></RESPONSIBILITY><RESPONSIBILITY RESP="IMG" WORKSTATUS="REV" WORKVALUE="C"><DATE>8 May 2011</DATE><ITEM></ITEM></RESPONSIBILITY><RESPONSIBILITY RESP="IMG" WORKSTATUS="RBV" WORKVALUE="C"><DATE>9 May 2011</DATE><ITEM>cft c, rbv c</ITEM></RESPONSIBILITY><RESPONSIBILITY RESP="IMG" WORKSTATUS="PUB" WORKVALUE="I"><DATE>31 May 2011</DATE><ITEM>pub i</ITEM></RESPONSIBILITY><RESPONSIBILITY RESP="MPO" WORKSTATUS="CFB" WORKVALUE="C"><DATE>3 June 2011</DATE><ITEM>cfb c, pilot 42</ITEM></RESPONSIBILITY><RESPONSIBILITY RESP="MPO" WORKSTATUS="CFT" WORKVALUE="C"><DATE>7 June 2011</DATE><ITEM>cft c, pilot42</ITEM></RESPONSIBILITY><RESPONSIBILITY WORKSTATUS="pub" RESP="MPO" WORKVALUE="c"><DATE>21 June 2011</DATE><ITEM>pub c, pilot42</ITEM></RESPONSIBILITY></REVISIONDESC></ORLANDOHEADER><DIV0><HEADING>Writing</HEADING><STANDARD>Johnson, Jane</STANDARD><AUTHORSUMMARY><SHORTPROSE><P>JJ, an eighteenth-century country clergyman&apos;s wife, published nothing, but she <QUOTE DIRECT="Y">used her writing to examine the meaning of her life and to confront its problems.</QUOTE><BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="Whyman 163" DBREF="63745">163</BIBCIT></BIBCITS> <GENERICRANGE>She left <TGENRE GENRENAME="LETTER">letters</TGENRE> (which incorporate <TGENRE GENRENAME="POETRY">poetry</TGENRE>, <TGENRE GENRENAME="FICTION">fiction</TGENRE>, and a <TGENRE GENRENAME="DREAMVISION">dream-vision</TGENRE>), <TGENRE GENRENAME="NOTEBOOK">notebooks</TGENRE>, more poems, <TGENRE GENRENAME="RELIGIOUS">religious</TGENRE> musings, <TGENRE GENRENAME="CHILDRENSLITERATURE">stories for her children</TGENRE> including the earliest known original <TGENRE GENRENAME="FAIRYTALE">fairy-tale</TGENRE> in English, and a set of ingenious <TGENRE GENRENAME="PEDAGOGY">teaching aids</TGENRE> known as a <SOCALLED>nursery library</SOCALLED>.</GENERICRANGE></P></SHORTPROSE></AUTHORSUMMARY><DIV1><HEADING>Letters</HEADING><DIV2><PRODUCTION><SHORTPROSE><P><PMATERIALCONDITIONS>Some of JJ&apos;s <TGENRE GENRENAME="LETTER">letters</TGENRE> are carefully written in a fine, legible hand; others are hastily scribbled.<BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="Whyman 175" DBREF="63745">175</BIBCIT></BIBCITS></PMATERIALCONDITIONS></P></SHORTPROSE></PRODUCTION><TEXTUALFEATURES><SHORTPROSE><P>JJ and her women friends used letters to discuss the <TTHEMETOPIC>books</TTHEMETOPIC> which each was eagerly reading. <NAME>Susan E. Whyman</NAME> writes that her letters disclose three passions: for her <TTHEMETOPIC>family</TTHEMETOPIC> (her children as they grew up became her correspondents), her <TTHEMETOPIC>religion</TTHEMETOPIC>, and her <TTHEMETOPIC>reading and writing</TTHEMETOPIC>. Her letters are both conversational and moral, with frequent use of narrative. Some include original passages of <TGENRE GENRENAME="POETRY">verse</TGENRE> <TINTERTEXTUALITY INTERTEXTTYPE="QUOTATION" GENDEROFAUTHOR="MALE">(borrowing on occasion a line or two from an obscure, older poet like <NAME>Phineas Fletcher</NAME>).</TINTERTEXTUALITY><BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="Whyman 163, 172, 175" DBREF="63745">163, 172, 175</BIBCIT></BIBCITS></P><P>She writes of <TTHEMETOPIC>women&apos;s virtues as domestic</TTHEMETOPIC> ones, and the <TTHEMETOPIC>family</TTHEMETOPIC> as <QUOTE DIRECT="Y">the proper province for private women to shine in.</QUOTE> Whyman likens her letters, in their aim and scope, to those of <NAME STANDARD="Richardson, Samuel">Richardson</NAME>.<BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="Whyman 176" DBREF="63745" QTDIN="QTDINYES">176</BIBCIT></BIBCITS> She also calls JJ&apos;s letters to her cousin <NAME>Rebecca Garth</NAME> (wife of John Garth, MP for Devizes) carefully designed <TGENRE GENRENAME="RELIGIOUS">religious</TGENRE> <TGENRE GENRENAME="ESSAY">essays</TGENRE>. In keeping with her <ORGNAME STANDARD="Anglican Church">Anglican</ORGNAME> allegiance, Johnson advises that <TTHEMETOPIC>religious observance</TTHEMETOPIC> should be not exaggerated or affected but subject to <TTHEMETOPIC>reason</TTHEMETOPIC>, and she adds some questioning about how far a <TTHEMETOPIC>husband is justified in seeking to control his wife</TTHEMETOPIC>&apos;s religious practice. <BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="Whyman 178-9 and n126" DBREF="63745">178-9 and n126</BIBCIT></BIBCITS></P><P>She can also be assertive in practical or business matters. Writing to the headmaster of <ORGNAME STANDARD="Uppingham School" REG="Uppingham Grammar School">Uppingham School</ORGNAME> (which had been founded by an ancestor of her husband) to complain that the <TTHEMETOPIC>fees</TTHEMETOPIC> are too high, she remarks that hogs would cost just as much to keep, and flatly states that she is sending good new sheets with her boys instead of their entrance money.<BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="Arizpe 41-2" DBREF="66568">41-2</BIBCIT></BIBCITS></P></SHORTPROSE></TEXTUALFEATURES><RECEPTION><SHORTPROSE><P><PMANUSCRIPTHISTORY>JJ preserved many but not all of her letters and other records. <RDESTRUCTIONOFWORK DESTROYEDBY="SELF">In filing the letters she instructed her correspondents which they should destroy (as, in cases where such instructions remain, they clearly did not). She bore her family&apos;s reputation in mind and elimininated from the record any words that she thought might damage it (though later and more prudish generations probably contributed, too, to the overall amount of destruction).<BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="Whyman 171" DBREF="63745">171</BIBCIT></BIBCITS></RDESTRUCTIONOFWORK></PMANUSCRIPTHISTORY></P></SHORTPROSE></RECEPTION><PRODUCTION><CHRONSTRUCT RESP="IMG" CHRONCOLUMN="BRITISHWOMENWRITERS" RELEVANCE="COMPREHENSIVE"><DATE>March 1739</DATE><CHRONPROSE><TTONESTYLE>JJ <TGENRE GENRENAME="LETTER">wrote to</TGENRE> a cousin about her <TTHEMETOPIC>one-year-old <NAME STANDARD="Johnson, Barbara">daughter</NAME></TTHEMETOPIC>, mocking the idea of seeking <TTHEMETOPIC>family resemblance</TTHEMETOPIC> in a child: <QUOTE DIRECT="Y">She is . . . as much like herself as ever you saw a little girl in your life</QUOTE></TTONESTYLE></CHRONPROSE><BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="Bodleian Library Record 167" DBREF="66628" QTDIN="QTDINYES">167</BIBCIT></BIBCITS></CHRONSTRUCT><SHORTPROSE><P>She makes fun, too, of the parental tendency to see one&apos;s child as perfect. <QUOTE DIRECT="Y">Her Papa and Mama think her the very finest child they ever saw with their eyes, but I do not believe there is one body living besides of that opinion.</QUOTE><BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="Bodleian Library Record 167" DBREF="66628" QTDIN="QTDINYES">167</BIBCIT></BIBCITS></P><P>Her letters to her children are charming, though she seems to have encouraged the kind of rivalry among them which <NAME>Samuel Johnson</NAME> deplored. In <DATE>November 1753</DATE>, when Robert was eight, she wrote to him: <QUOTE DIRECT="Y">I think my Robert will not be such a fool to let a little boy out do him, a little boy [his brother Woolsey] almost two and a half years younger than yourself.</QUOTE> But nearly two years later she told Robert: <QUOTE DIRECT="Y">I love you dearly, &amp; think you one of the most sensible children of your age in the world.</QUOTE><BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="Bodleian Library Record 166" DBREF="66628" QTDIN="QTDINYES">166</BIBCIT></BIBCITS></P></SHORTPROSE></PRODUCTION></DIV2><DIV2><HEADING><TITLE TITLETYPE="UNPUBLISHED" REG="History of Miss Clarissa of Buckinghamshire, The">The History of Miss Clarissa of Buckinghamshire</TITLE></HEADING><PRODUCTION><CHRONSTRUCT RESP="IMG" CHRONCOLUMN="BRITISHWOMENWRITERS" RELEVANCE="DECADE"><DATE>17 October 1749</DATE><CHRONPROSE><TINTERTEXTUALITY INTERTEXTTYPE="ADAPTATION-UPDATE" GENDEROFAUTHOR="MALE"><TSETTINGPLACE SETTINGPLACETYPE="REAL" SETTINGCLASS="WIDERANGE"><TSETTINGPLACE SETTINGPLACETYPE="REAL" SETTINGCLASS="MIDDLECLASS">JJ interrupted a <TGENRE GENRENAME="LETTER">letter</TGENRE> of tentative <TTHEMETOPIC>moral advice</TTHEMETOPIC> to her friend Mrs Brompton, to cast her thoughts into <TGENRE GENRENAME="SHORTSTORY">fiction</TGENRE>: <TITLE TITLETYPE="UNPUBLISHED">The History of Miss <TCHARACTERNAME>Clarissa</TCHARACTERNAME> of <PLACE><REGION>Buckinghamshire</REGION><GEOG REG="England"></GEOG></PLACE></TITLE>,</TSETTINGPLACE> <TINTERTEXTUALITY INTERTEXTTYPE="ALLUSIONACKNOWLEDGED" GENDEROFAUTHOR="MALE">who is descended from <TTHEMETOPIC><NAME STANDARD="Richardson, Samuel">Richardson</NAME>&apos;s Clarissa</TTHEMETOPIC>, but much less sorely tried.</TINTERTEXTUALITY></TSETTINGPLACE></TINTERTEXTUALITY></CHRONPROSE><BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="Whyman 179-181 and n135" DBREF="63745">179-181 and n135</BIBCIT></BIBCITS></CHRONSTRUCT><SHORTPROSE><P>The history is crowded onto both sides of three large sheets of paper. The letter ends with a <TGENRE GENRENAME="LITERARYCRITICISM">defence</TGENRE> of Richardson&apos;s novel against the only person of generally good judgement whom JJ has met who dislikes it.<BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="Whyman 180, 183" DBREF="63745">180, 183</BIBCIT></BIBCITS></P></SHORTPROSE></PRODUCTION><TEXTUALFEATURES><SHORTPROSE><P>Her Clarissa (a neighbour who, says JJ,  is thus called <QUOTE DIRECT="Y">because I take pleasure in the name</QUOTE>)<BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="Whyman fig. 32" DBREF="63745">fig. 32</BIBCIT></BIBCITS>is comfortably married to a gentleman with sufficient money, and devotes her <TTHEMETOPIC>leisure to handiworks</TTHEMETOPIC>, making ingenious gifts for friends. A dangerous <TMOTIF>illness</TMOTIF>, however, makes her wonder fearfully if this is really an adequate use of her precious time. She is <TMOTIF MOTIFNAME="conversion, religious">converted to <TTHEMETOPIC>good works</TTHEMETOPIC></TMOTIF>, and henceforth spends her time <TTHEMETOPIC>visiting the poor</TTHEMETOPIC> and <TTHEMETOPIC>dispensing carefully-judged charity</TTHEMETOPIC>, defying the gossips who might class such activity as <ORGNAME STANDARD="Methodist Church">Methodist</ORGNAME>.<BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="Whyman 180-1" DBREF="63745">180-1</BIBCIT></BIBCITS> Most interestingly of all, this Clarissa begins to develop a <TTHEMETOPIC>political consciousness</TTHEMETOPIC>. <QUOTE DIRECT="Y">There must certainly be some great fault somewhere,</QUOTE> she muses, <QUOTE DIRECT="Y">either in the Laws, or in the actions of Individuals . . . since God does every year send vastly more Corn, Meat, Wool, Flax, &amp; Hemp than it is possible for all the Inhabitants of the Land to consume.</QUOTE> <TTHEMETOPIC>Clothing the naked</TTHEMETOPIC>, she points out, would even promote trade. <QUOTE DIRECT="Y">She allows that many good <TTHEMETOPIC>Laws have been made for the relief of the Poor</TTHEMETOPIC>, but she thinks many better might be made, were the Hearts of Both <TTHEMETOPIC>Houses of Parliament</TTHEMETOPIC> as good as their Heads.</QUOTE><BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="Whyman 182" DBREF="63745" QTDIN="QTDINYES">182</BIBCIT></BIBCITS></P></SHORTPROSE></TEXTUALFEATURES></DIV2><DIV2><HEADING>Author as Spider</HEADING><PRODUCTION><CHRONSTRUCT RESP="IMG" CHRONCOLUMN="BRITISHWOMENWRITERS" RELEVANCE="COMPREHENSIVE"><DATE>28 February 1756</DATE><CHRONPROSE><TTECHNIQUES TECHNIQUETYPE="IMAGERY">JJ addressed to a Mrs Brompton a <TGENRE GENRENAME="LETTER">letter</TGENRE> incorporating an elaborate <TGENRE GENRENAME="DREAMVISION">dream-vision</TGENRE> of herself spinning an enormous web, and sitting at its centre <QUOTE DIRECT="Y"><TCHARACTERNAME>Arachne</TCHARACTERNAME> like</QUOTE>, enthroned, <QUOTE DIRECT="Y">as big as the full moon.</QUOTE></TTECHNIQUES></CHRONPROSE><BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="Whyman 177 and n121" DBREF="63745">177 and n121</BIBCIT></BIBCITS></CHRONSTRUCT><SHORTPROSE><P><PMATERIALCONDITIONS>Writing just before her husband died,<BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="Arizpe 34" DBREF="66568">34</BIBCIT></BIBCITS></PMATERIALCONDITIONS> she goes on to contrast the <TTHEMETOPIC>natural beauty of the countryside</TTHEMETOPIC> under moonlight and hoarfrost with the jewelled beauties of the court.<BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="Whyman 177-8" DBREF="63745">177-8</BIBCIT></BIBCITS></P></SHORTPROSE></PRODUCTION></DIV2><DIV2><PRODUCTION><SHORTPROSE><P>On <DATE>9 May 1750</DATE> JJ <TGENRE GENRENAME="LETTER">wrote to</TGENRE> her son George, who was not yet ten, <QUOTE DIRECT="Y">thank you for your very pretty Letter.</QUOTE> She wrote to express her confidence that he was <QUOTE DIRECT="Y">improving in every thing</QUOTE> and to assure him that she was <QUOTE DIRECT="Y">vastly fond of you.</QUOTE> <PRARITIESFEATURESDECORATIONS>She included a sketch of George, with two friends and adult escort, <QUOTE DIRECT="Y">coming from Rugby School</QUOTE> on horseback.</PRARITIESFEATURESDECORATIONS><BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="Whyman fig. 31" DBREF="63745">fig. 31</BIBCIT></BIBCITS></P></SHORTPROSE></PRODUCTION></DIV2></DIV1><DIV1><HEADING>Teaching her Children</HEADING><DIV2><PRODUCTION><SHORTPROSE><P>One of JJ&apos;s teaching tools was a <QUOTE DIRECT="Y">homemade nursery library</QUOTE> dating from the 1740s: a box or <QUOTE DIRECT="Y"><TGENRE GENRENAME="PEDAGOGY">teaching</TGENRE> kit</QUOTE> containing mobiles, <TGENRE GENRENAME="POETRY">verses</TGENRE>, <QUOTE DIRECT="Y">word chips</QUOTE>, sets of illustrated letter cards (by which letters can be gathered into syllables and syllables into words), and <TGENRE GENRENAME="CHILDRENSLITERATURE">little hand-made books</TGENRE>.<BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="Whyman 166-7" DBREF="63745">166-7</BIBCIT><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="Paul 83" DBREF="66567">83</BIBCIT></BIBCITS> <PARCHIVALLOCATION>The nursery library, in 438 pieces, was collected by <NAME>George Ball</NAME> of the US Midwest in the 1930s and was rediscovered a few years ago in an old hatbox, together with other material by and about JJ and her family.<BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="Arizpe v" DBREF="66568">v</BIBCIT></BIBCITS>The whole collection, now in the <ORGNAME>Lilly Library</ORGNAME> at the <ORGNAME>University of Indiana</ORGNAME> at <PLACE><SETTLEMENT>Bloomington</SETTLEMENT><REGION REG="Indiana"></REGION><GEOG REG="USA"></GEOG></PLACE>,</PARCHIVALLOCATION> is digitally available through the university&apos;s website. <PRARITIESFEATURESDECORATIONS>It is well illustrated in black and white and in colour in <TITLE TITLETYPE="MONOGRAPHIC">Reading Lessons from the Eighteenth Century: Mothers, Children and Texts</TITLE> by <NAME>Evelyn Arizpe</NAME> and others.</PRARITIESFEATURESDECORATIONS><BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="Whyman 167 and n30" DBREF="63745">167 and n30</BIBCIT><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="Arizpe esp. 96-97" DBREF="66568">esp. 96-7</BIBCIT></BIBCITS></P></SHORTPROSE></PRODUCTION><RECEPTION><SHORTPROSE><P><RRESPONSES RESPONSETYPE="RECENT" FORMALITY="FORMAL"><NAME>Evelyn Arizpe</NAME>, <NAME>Morag Styles</NAME>, and <NAME>Shirley Brice Heath</NAME> have commended <TTONESTYLE>JJ for her insight that <QUOTE DIRECT="Y"><TTHEMETOPIC>learning to read</TTHEMETOPIC> requires frivolity, storytelling and diversion as well as diligence, rigour and repetition.</QUOTE></TTONESTYLE><BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="Arizpe et al 92" DBREF="66568">92</BIBCIT></BIBCITS> <NAME>Lissa Paul</NAME> calls the nursery library <QUOTE DIRECT="Y">enticing and beautiful.</QUOTE><BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="Paul 83" DBREF="66567">83</BIBCIT></BIBCITS></RRESPONSES></P></SHORTPROSE></RECEPTION></DIV2><DIV2><HEADING><TITLE TITLETYPE="MONOGRAPHIC">A Very Pretty Story</TITLE></HEADING><TEXTSCOPE DBREF="66569" PLACEHOLDER="JJ, A Very Pretty Story, 2001"></TEXTSCOPE><PRODUCTION><CHRONSTRUCT RESP="MPO" CHRONCOLUMN="BRITISHWOMENWRITERS" RELEVANCE="SELECTIVE"><DATE VALUE="1745--" CERTAINTY="C">1744 or 1745</DATE><CHRONPROSE><PINFLUENCESHER INFLUENCETYPE="INTELLECTUAL"><RLANDMARKTEXT>Inspired by the use of stories in <TGENRE GENRENAME="PEDAGOGY">family education</TGENRE> by <NAME STANDARD="Richardson, Samuel">Richardson</NAME>&apos;s Pamela, JJ wrote, printed and bound for her daughter and eldest son <TITLE TITLETYPE="UNPUBLISHED" REG=" Very Pretty Story, A">A very pretty <TGENRE GENRENAME="CHILDRENSLITERATURE">story to tell Children</TGENRE> when they are about five or six years of age</TITLE>.</RLANDMARKTEXT></PINFLUENCESHER></CHRONPROSE><BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="Whyman 167" DBREF="63745">167</BIBCIT></BIBCITS></CHRONSTRUCT><SHORTPROSE><P>The manuscript also contains fair copies of ten <TGENRE GENRENAME="POETRY">poems</TGENRE> and a <TGENRE GENRENAME="PRAYER">prayer</TGENRE>.<BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="Bodleian Library Record 166" DBREF="66628" QTDIN="QTDINYES">166</BIBCIT></BIBCITS> <NAME>John Newbery</NAME> published a similar tale, <TITLE TITLETYPE="MONOGRAPHIC">A Little Pretty Pocket-Book</TITLE>, in 1744. <PEDITIONS>JJ&apos;s work did not reach actual print <PRARITIESFEATURESDECORATIONS>(as opposed to the formal hand in which she imitated print)</PRARITIESFEATURESDECORATIONS> until a facsimile edition was produced by the <ORGNAME STANDARD="Bodleian Library">Bodleian</ORGNAME> in 2001 as <TITLE TITLETYPE="MONOGRAPHIC" REG="Very Pretty Story, A">A Very Pretty Story, A Facsimile of the MS held in the Bodleian Library</TITLE>, with an introduction by <NAME>Gillian Avery</NAME>. It includes a modern text and a facsimile of the copy in JJ&apos;s own formal handwriting.<BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="Whyman 167n33" DBREF="63745">167n33</BIBCIT><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="Bodleian" DBREF="9935"></BIBCIT></BIBCITS></PEDITIONS></P></SHORTPROSE></PRODUCTION><TEXTUALFEATURES><SHORTPROSE><P><TCHARACTERIZATION>The child heroine and hero are generally known by honorific titles as Miss and Master, but their names of Bab and George link them with the author&apos;s own two eldest.</TCHARACTERIZATION> The story is heavily moralised. The children are improbably perfect creatures, <TPLOT>who when their two <TMOTIF MOTIFNAME="orphan">playfellows are orphaned</TMOTIF> and then <TMOTIF MOTIFNAME="financial ruin">left destitute</TMOTIF> by a <TCHARACTERTYPEROLE>wicked uncle</TCHARACTERTYPEROLE>, beg their parents to come to the <TMOTIF>rescue</TMOTIF> and adopt them. The resulting foursome play happily together, never quarrelling, until Master Tommy goes to the bad. He wastes his money, steals George&apos;s share instead, and lays the blame on a maid who is therefore dismissed. <TSETTINGPLACE SETTINGPLACETYPE="FICTIVE">When supernatural visitants appear to take the children to the <TMOTIF MOTIFNAME="castle">Castle</TMOTIF> of Pleasure and Delights, Tommy is punished instead, while the others enjoy travelling in a gold and diamond chariot drawn by six white lambs, with angels as outriders</TSETTINGPLACE></TPLOT> (an advance on the coach and horses which in children&apos;s stories of this time and later is generally the hard-earned reward for good conduct).</P></SHORTPROSE></TEXTUALFEATURES><RECEPTION><SHORTPROSE><P><RRESPONSES RESPONSETYPE="INITIAL" FORMALITY="INFORMAL"><NAME STANDARD="Johnson, Barbara">Barbara</NAME> and George Johnson <QUOTE DIRECT="Y">took Vast Delight in hearing [this story] told over &amp; over.</QUOTE><BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="Bodleian Library Record 166" DBREF="66628" QTDIN="QTDINYES">166</BIBCIT></BIBCITS></RRESPONSES> <RRESPONSES RESPONSETYPE="RECENT" FORMALITY="FORMAL"><RLANDMARKTEXT>A member of the <ORGNAME STANDARD="Bodleian Library">Bodleian</ORGNAME> staff called this notebook <QUOTE DIRECT="Y">an important manuscript in the history of children&apos;s literature.</QUOTE><BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="Bodleian Library Record 165" DBREF="66628">165</BIBCIT></BIBCITS></RLANDMARKTEXT> <NAME>Susan E. Whyman</NAME>, oddly, pronounces it non-moralistic.</RRESPONSES></P></SHORTPROSE></RECEPTION></DIV2></DIV1><DIV1><HEADING>Notebooks</HEADING><DIV2><PRODUCTION><SHORTPROSE><P><PMANUSCRIPTHISTORY>JJ kept several <TGENRE GENRENAME="NOTEBOOK">notebooks</TGENRE>, into one of which she transcribed those of her <SOCALLED>literary</SOCALLED> writings that she wished to preserve: her own prose and poetry, as well as <TGENRE GENRENAME="COMMONPLACEBOOK">excerpts copied from other texts</TGENRE>. She began to fill her <TGENRE GENRENAME="COOKBOOK">recipe book</TGENRE> before she was married.<BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="Whyman 167" DBREF="63745">167</BIBCIT><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="Bodleian mss catalogue, Papers of Jane Johnson" DBREF="66565"></BIBCIT></BIBCITS></PMANUSCRIPTHISTORY></P></SHORTPROSE></PRODUCTION></DIV2><DIV2><HEADING>Commonplace-Book</HEADING><PRODUCTION><SHORTPROSE><P>Here JJ mixed the intellectual or spiritual with the <TGENRE GENRENAME="COOKBOOK">practical</TGENRE>: the same page bears a <TTHEMETOPIC>recipe for syllabub</TTHEMETOPIC> and the sentiment <QUOTE DIRECT="Y">I had rather be a favourite of Angels than of men, but I believe those that Behave as they should do, will commonly be a favourite of both.</QUOTE><BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="Arizpe 17" DBREF="66568" QTDIN="QTDINYES">17</BIBCIT></BIBCITS> The emphasis, however, falls on her reading. She <QUOTE DIRECT="Y">read extensively like a magpie,</QUOTE><BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="Whyman 189" DBREF="63745">189</BIBCIT></BIBCITS> and made <TGENRE GENRENAME="COMMONPLACEBOOK">extracts</TGENRE> from what she read. Between the excerpts she would write her comments.<BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="Whyman 167" DBREF="63745">167</BIBCIT></BIBCITS> She signed and dated her own remarks, <PMOTIVES MOTIVETYPE="SELF-IDENTIFIED">and evidently envisaged a reader or readers, whom she informed: <QUOTE DIRECT="Y">All the Paragraphs marked thus + are my own.</QUOTE><BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="Whyman 168" DBREF="63745" QTDIN="QTDINYES">168</BIBCIT></BIBCITS></PMOTIVES> <TINTERTEXTUALITY INTERTEXTTYPE="QUOTATION" GENDEROFAUTHOR="MALE">Poets from whom she took excerpts ranged from the widely popular <NAME STANDARD="Thomson, James,, 1700 - 1748">James Thomson</NAME> to, surprisingly, the evangelicals <NAME>James Hervey</NAME> and her enemy <NAME>Moses Browne</NAME>. A list of the writers she excerpts includes no women.<BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="Whyman 185 n158, 187" DBREF="63745">185 n158, 187</BIBCIT><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="Arizpe 210-15" DBREF="66568">210-15</BIBCIT></BIBCITS></TINTERTEXTUALITY></P></SHORTPROSE></PRODUCTION></DIV2><DIV2><HEADING>Meditations</HEADING><PRODUCTION><SHORTPROSE><P>One notebook she kept for <TGENRE GENRENAME="RELIGIOUS">religious</TGENRE> musings, <TGENRE GENRENAME="PRAYER">prayers</TGENRE>, and <TGENRE GENRENAME="DEVOTIONAL">devotional</TGENRE> writing.<BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="Whyman 167" DBREF="63745">167</BIBCIT><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="Bodleian mss catalogue, Papers of Jane Johnson" DBREF="66565"></BIBCIT></BIBCITS></P></SHORTPROSE></PRODUCTION></DIV2><DIV2><HEADING>Poetry</HEADING><PRODUCTION><SHORTPROSE><P><TTONESTYLE>JJ also wrote <TGENRE GENRENAME="POETRY">poetry</TGENRE>, both light-hearted <TGENRE GENRENAME="OCCASIONALPOETRY">occasional verse</TGENRE> and more serious efforts.</TTONESTYLE> The former mode is exemplified by <TITLE TITLETYPE="UNPUBLISHED"><TGENRE GENRENAME="EPISTLE">Invitation</TGENRE> to Miss <NAME>Barbara Johnson</NAME> to come into the country</TITLE>, dated <DATE>1 May 1747</DATE>, addressed to her not quite nine-year-old daughter. Poems of the latter kind include a <TGENRE GENRENAME="SONNET">sonnet</TGENRE> <TITLE TITLETYPE="ANALYTIC">On <TTHEMETOPIC>Wisdom</TTHEMETOPIC></TITLE>. The sonnet brings <TTHEMETOPIC>reason</TTHEMETOPIC> and <TTHEMETOPIC>religion</TTHEMETOPIC> together, arguing that wisdom will enable the speaker to keep God&apos;s commandments.<BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="Bodleian mss catalogue, Papers of Jane Johnson" DBREF="66565"></BIBCIT><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="Arizpe 35-6" DBREF="66568">35-6</BIBCIT></BIBCITS> <PMANUSCRIPTHISTORY><PRARITIESFEATURESDECORATIONS>On at least one occasion she made a beautiful transcript of a more ambitious poem in the format of a printed book, with title page, epigraph, <QUOTE DIRECT="Y">decorative lined borders, numbered pages, and even a footnote</QUOTE></PRARITIESFEATURESDECORATIONS>&mdash;although even after making the fair copy she continued to make alterations.</PMANUSCRIPTHISTORY> This poem, written in 1747, is called <TITLE TITLETYPE="UNPUBLISHED">A conversation between <TCHARACTERNAME>Stella</TCHARACTERNAME> &amp; her guardian Angel, One Star Light Night, in the Garden at &mdash;</TITLE>.<BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="Whyman 185" DBREF="63745">185</BIBCIT><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="Arizpe 37" DBREF="66568">37</BIBCIT></BIBCITS></P></SHORTPROSE></PRODUCTION><TEXTUALFEATURES><SHORTPROSE><P><TINTERTEXTUALITY INTERTEXTTYPE="QUOTATION" GENDEROFAUTHOR="MALE">The poem is headed with a quotation from <TITLE TITLETYPE="ANALYTIC" REG="Bible" REND="normal">Psalm</TITLE> 19: <QUOTE DIRECT="Y">The Heavens declare the Glory of God, &amp; the Firmament showeth his handy work</QUOTE>&mdash;the same psalm which <NAME STANDARD="Addison, Joseph">Addison</NAME> had famously rendered as <QUOTE DIRECT="Y">The spacious firmament on high.</QUOTE><BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="Whyman 185" DBREF="63745" QTDIN="QTDINYES">185</BIBCIT></BIBCITS></TINTERTEXTUALITY> Johnson&apos;s Stella looks forward to the <TTHEMETOPIC>next life</TTHEMETOPIC>, to slipping the <TTHEMETOPIC>bounds of time and space</TTHEMETOPIC>, as speakers had done in poems by <NAME STANDARD="Pope, Alexander">Pope</NAME> and <NAME>Elizabeth Carter</NAME>. Her happiness after death will involve touring the <TTHEMETOPIC>cosmos, and above all learning the secrets of its operations</TTHEMETOPIC>. <QUOTE DIRECT="Y">To View the Expanse! the Vast <TTHEMETOPIC>Universe</TTHEMETOPIC> scan! / And be certain what Distance each star is from man!</QUOTE> <TINTERTEXTUALITY INTERTEXTTYPE="ALLUSIONACKNOWLEDGED" GENDEROFAUTHOR="MALE">She will then know whether <TTHEMETOPIC>other worlds are inhabited</TTHEMETOPIC>, and <QUOTE DIRECT="Y">how far the great <NAME STANDARD="Newton, Sir Isaac">Newton</NAME> with Truth does agree.</QUOTE> More than that, she will <QUOTE DIRECT="Y">be in an instant much Wiser than He!</QUOTE></TINTERTEXTUALITY> <TINTERTEXTUALITY INTERTEXTTYPE="ALLUSIONUNACKNOWLEDGED" GENDEROFAUTHOR="MALE">Stella is then conducted around the universe by the <TCHARACTERTYPEROLE>archangel</TCHARACTERTYPEROLE> <TCHARACTERNAME>Raphael</TCHARACTERNAME><BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="Whyman 186" DBREF="63745" QTDIN="QTDINYES">186</BIBCIT></BIBCITS> (who is also a source of information in <NAME STANDARD="Milton, John"></NAME><TITLE TITLETYPE="MONOGRAPHIC">Paradise Lost</TITLE>, but who there sets limits to what humans are allowed to know). Johnson&apos;s Raphael engages freely in <TGENRE GENRENAME="DIALOGUEORDEBATE">dialogue</TGENRE> with Stella in the later part of the poem, discussing <TTHEMETOPIC>theological as well as scientific questions</TTHEMETOPIC>.<BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="Whyman 187" DBREF="63745">187</BIBCIT></BIBCITS></TINTERTEXTUALITY></P></SHORTPROSE></TEXTUALFEATURES></DIV2></DIV1><DIV1><DIV2><PRODUCTION><SHORTPROSE><P><PARCHIVALLOCATION>JJ&apos;s papers are divided between the <ORGNAME>Bodleian Library</ORGNAME> (which also holds the archives of several of her relations) and the <ORGNAME>Lilly Library</ORGNAME>.<BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="Whyman 162 and n1" DBREF="63745">162 and n1</BIBCIT><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="Papers of Jane Johnson" DBREF="66565"></BIBCIT><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="Lilly Library Johnson MSS" DBREF="66547"></BIBCIT></BIBCITS></PARCHIVALLOCATION></P></SHORTPROSE></PRODUCTION></DIV2></DIV1><WORKSCITED><SOURCE>Unless otherwise noted, all information is from the FC.</SOURCE><SOURCE>Arizpe et al.</SOURCE><SOURCE>Bodleian Library Record.</SOURCE><SOURCE>Lilly Library. Johnson MSS.</SOURCE><SOURCE>Paul.</SOURCE><SOURCE>Whyman, Susan E.</SOURCE></WORKSCITED></DIV0></WRITING>